# Quantum Education Backend — Project Conventions

## What This Project Is

Quantum Education is an **e-commerce platform + LMS (Learning Management System) for beauty
courses** (makeup, skincare, hairstyling, etc.). A single backend serves both web and future
mobile apps. Users can browse and purchase courses, and then consume the course content through
the built-in LMS.

### Key Domain Concepts

- **Users** sign up, verify email, log in. Roles: `USER` (customer) and `ADMIN` (course creator / platform admin).
- **Products** are purchasable course listings with pricing, descriptions, images.
- **Ownership** tracks which users own which products (post-purchase).
- **Cart** handles add-to-cart, checkout, and payment integration.
- **LMS** delivers course content (videos, materials, progress tracking) to users who own the course.

## Tech Stack

- Java 21, Spring Boot 3.3.5, Maven, MySQL 8, Lombok 1.18.38
- JWT (HS256) via jjwt, Argon2 password hashing, Spring Mail

## Architecture — Modular Monolith

```
quantum-edu-be/
├── pom.xml              # Parent POM
├── modules/
│   ├── common/          # Shared DTOs, response format, base exceptions
│   ├── auth/            # Authentication & authorization
│   ├── user-management/ # User profile CRUD
│   ├── product-catalogue/ (planned) # Course listings, pricing, images
│   ├── ownership/         (planned) # Purchase records, entitlements
│   ├── cart/              (planned) # Shopping cart, checkout, payment
│   └── lms/               (planned) # Course content delivery, progress
└── app/                 # Runnable Spring Boot application
```

### Module Status & Roadmap

| Module | Status | Purpose |
|--------|--------|---------|
| common | Done | `ApiResponse`, `ApiError`, `ErrorDetail`, `BaseApiException` |
| auth | Done | Signup, login, email verification, JWT, Argon2 |
| user-management | Done | User profile creation & retrieval (internal API) |
| product-catalogue | Planned | CRUD for courses/products, categories, images, pricing |
| ownership | Planned | Records of which user owns which product after purchase |
| cart | Planned | Add-to-cart, quantity management, checkout flow, payment |
| lms | Planned | Course content (modules/lessons/videos), progress tracking |

### Inter-Module Dependency Map

```
auth ──depends-on──▶ user-management (creates profile on signup)
cart ──depends-on──▶ ownership (record purchase after payment)
bff  ──depends-on──▶ product-catalogue (fetch featured products for page composition)
lms  ──will-depend──▶ ownership (check user owns course before granting access)
lms  ──will-depend──▶ product-catalogue (fetch course structure/content)
app  ──depends-on──▶ all modules (wires everything into one Spring Boot app)
```

### Module Rules

- Each module owns its own package: `com.quantum.edu.<module>` (e.g. `auth`, `usermgmt`).
- **Never** import another module's internal classes (repositories, domain entities, internal services).
- Cross-module communication uses the target module's **public API interface** (e.g. `UserProfileApi`).
- Only the `app` module has `@SpringBootApplication` and `spring-boot-maven-plugin`.
- New modules: create under `modules/`, add to parent POM `<modules>`, add to `app/pom.xml` dependencies.

### API Versioning

All REST endpoints are prefixed: `/api/v1/<module>/...`

## Standard API Response Format

Every controller returns `ResponseEntity<ApiResponse<T>>`.

```java
// Success
ApiResponse.success(responseDto)

// Error (handled via GlobalExceptionHandler)
ApiResponse.error(ApiError.of("QE_AUTH_001", "Validation failed", details))
```

- Success: `{ "success": true, "response": { ... } }`
- Error: `{ "success": false, "error": { "code": "QE_xxx", "message": "...", "details": [...] } }`
- `details` is an optional list of `ErrorDetail(field, message)` for validation errors.

## Error Handling

- Module-specific exceptions extend `BaseApiException` (in common module).
- Use static factory methods on exception classes: `AuthException.emailAlreadyExists()`.
- Error codes are prefixed per module: `QE_AUTH_xxx`, `QE_UM_xxx`, `QE_PC_xxx`, `QE_OWN_xxx`, `QE_CART_xxx`, `QE_LMS_xxx`, `QE_001` (global).
- `GlobalExceptionHandler` (in `app`) catches `BaseApiException`, `MethodArgumentNotValidException`, and generic `Exception`.
- Never throw raw `RuntimeException` from service code — always use a typed exception.

## Security Model (Current & Planned)

- **Auth**: JWT tokens issued on login, validated via filter on protected endpoints.
- **Public endpoints**: signup, login, verify-email, resend-verification, product browsing.
- **Protected endpoints**: profile updates, cart operations, purchases, LMS content access.
- **Admin endpoints**: product CRUD, user management admin views (role-gated).

## Database Conventions

- MySQL 8 with InnoDB.
- Table names: `snake_case` matching the entity concept (e.g. `auth_user`, `user_profile`).
- All PKs are `Long` with `@GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)` (MySQL auto-increment).
- All entities have `created_at` and `updated_at` (`Instant`, not null).
- Column names: `snake_case`. JPA `@Column(name = "...")` explicit on every field.
- Indexes: declared via `@Table(indexes = ...)` or `@Index`.

## Configuration (application.properties / application-*.properties)

**Rule: Every new or edited config must exist in every environment.**

- **Environments:** `application.properties` (base), `application-dev.properties`, `application-staging.properties`, `application-prod.properties`.
- **When adding a new config property:**
  1. Add it to the base `application.properties` if it has sensible defaults.
  2. Add it to **every** env-specific file: `application-dev.properties`, `application-staging.properties`, `application-prod.properties`.
  3. If the value for an env is unknown, add a **placeholder** and a **TODO comment** (e.g. `# TODO: provide actual value for prod`).
- **When editing an existing config:**
  1. **Ask the user** for values for all other environments (dev, staging, prod) before making changes.
  2. After user confirmation, update **all** env files consistently.
- **Goal:** No inconsistency between environments. Any agent working with properties or YAML must ensure all envs are updated together.

## Documentation

API specs live in `docs/`: `AUTH_API_SPEC.md`, `USER_MANAGEMENT_API_SPEC.md`, `API_RESPONSE_FORMAT.md`, `MODULAR_ARCHITECTURE.md`. When adding a new module with REST APIs, create a corresponding `docs/<MODULE>_API_SPEC.md`.
